03857nam a2200517Ia 9782759834815DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024fr     fo  d z      eng d  a97827598348157 a10.1051/978-2-7598-3481-52doi  a(DE-B1597)690189  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  afrcFR 7aSCI0000002bisacsh1 aBracco, Christian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen Albert became Einstein :b1895-1901 /cChristian Bracco. 1aLes Ulis : bEDP Sciences, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (150 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSciences et Histoire00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Italian political and industrial context of the 19th Century -- t2 The company of Jakob and Hermann Einstein in the international electrotechnical context – exhibitions and reviews -- t3 Michele Besso and his family’s role in Italian industrialisation -- t4 Albert’s environment in Pavia and preparations for ETH -- t5 Albert’s scientific environment in Milan -- t6 Three Albert’s scientific questionings (1898-1901) in connection with his later 1905 work -- tA final word -- tIndex of names -- tSelected bibliography -- tAcknowledgements0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book proposes an in-depth investigation carried out in Italy in young Albert Einstein's footsteps, since his attempt to enter the ETH Zurich in 1895 until his first doctoral work in 1901. We follow his family, who transferred his electrical engineering company from Munich to Milan, in the rich social, economic, political and industrial context of post-unified Italy; a milieu also familiar to Michele Besso, Albert's closest friend and collaborator, whom he met again daily in Milan on semester-breaks, after their first meeting in 1895. In Pavia, the parish register will lead us to Carlo Marangoni, the uncle of Ernestina (Albert's friend) and a specialist in capillarity phenomena. In Milan, we will discover the library of the Lombardo Institute, Academy of sciences and letters, where Albert worked for his bibliography.Old registers at the university and at the Polytechnic will draw our attention to his connection with Giuseppe Jung, one of Michele's uncles, an academician.This young Albert environment sheds a new light on his scientific remarks to his fiancée Mileva Marié: his first article on capillarity and molecular forces; his interest in wireless telegraphy; his search to evidence the motion of the Earth through the ether; his thesis extended to weakly compressed gases and even his early questionings on the nature of light. All of this we will discover in a trip round Lombardy in the beginning of the 19th century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1051/978-2-7598-3481-540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9782759834815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9782759834815/original  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles